{
 "cells": [
  {
   "kind": 1,
   "value": "(*Standalone numerical solver for the L=2 su(2) XXX Baxter (TQ) equation.\nThis file is SELF-CONTAINED: it defines every symbol it uses (θ1,θ2,h,κ1,κ2, aFun, Qθ=d, τ0,\nBaxterMatrix, the transfer-matrix machinery ps/dim/J0/Jp/Jm/JJ/Ee/L/G/L1/L2/T/t2, TauEigensystem,\nPsi, τ, QSolve, Q1) and runs top-to-bottom from a fresh kernel.\n\nBaxter equation:  a(u) Q(u+h) - τ(u) Q(u) + d(u) Q(u-h) = 0, with\n  a(u) = (u-θ1-h λ1)(u-θ2-h λ2)   [B2 eigenvalue at s1=λ1,s2=λ2, top of SoV lattice]\n  d(u) = (u-θ1)(u-θ2) = Qθ[u]     [B2 eigenvalue at s1=s2=0, bottom of SoV lattice]\n  κ2 = 1/κ1                       [twist eigenvalues, simplifying assumption; also |κ1|=1 here,\n                                    i.e. κ2=Conjugate[κ1] exactly, a fact used below]\n  τ(u) = u^2(κ1+κ2) - u(θ1+θ2)(κ1+κ2) - u h(κ1 ee1 + κ2 ee2) + J\n where ee1,ee2 are eigenvalues of EE[1,1],EE[2,2] with ee1+ee2 = λ1+λ2 (central charge), and J is\n the quantum number distinguishing states of a given magnon number. Magnon sector M is defined by\n ee1 = λ1+λ2-M, hence ee2 = M, with M = 0..λ1+λ2. τ0(u) := τ(u)-J (the J-independent part).\n\n===== WHY THIS FILE WAS REFORMULATED: the Baxter-matrix-first approach produces SPURIOUS states =====\n\nThe natural-looking first attempt is: for fixed (λ1,λ2,M), write the ansatz Q(u)=κ1^(u/h) q(u)\nwith q(u) a MONIC polynomial of degree M, build the (M+1)x(M+1) coefficient matrix of the linear\noperator O[q](u) := κ1 a(u) q(u+h) + κ2 d(u) q(u-h) - τ0(u) q(u) acting on span{1,u,...,u^M}, and\nDIAGONALIZE it: eigenvalues are candidate J_n, eigenvectors give q_n(u), for n=0,...,M.\n\nThis is WRONG in general. It manufactures exactly M+1 candidates for every M=0,...,λ1+λ2, but the\ntrue weight-M subspace of Vλ1⊗Vλ2 (the space the transfer matrix t2 actually acts on) has dimension\ndPred(M) = Min[M,λ1,λ2,λ1+λ2-M]+1, which is STRICTLY LESS than M+1 once M > Min[λ1,λ2]. E.g. for\n(λ1,λ2)=(2,1) the M=2 sector has dPred=2, but the Baxter-matrix approach naively produces 3\ncandidates (n=0,1,2) — one of them (n=2) is a root of the (M+1)-dimensional Baxter-matrix problem\nthat does NOT correspond to any actual transfer-matrix eigenstate. Such solutions still solve the\ndegree-M polynomial recursion formally, but there is no genuine Q-function/eigenstate behind them.\nThe only way to tell genuine from spurious was to build the eigenstate independently afterward\n(via a stacked-nullspace construction against the actual transfer matrix) and FILTER — i.e. build\nfirst, ask questions later, discovering which candidates were fake only after the fact.\n\nThis causality is backwards: we already know exactly how many genuine states exist and what\ndistinguishes them (real representation theory, encoded in dPred), so DERIVE the genuine states\nFIRST from the actual transfer matrix, and only THEN solve for their Q-functions.\n\n===== NEW FLOW: genuine transfer-matrix eigenstates first, TQ equation as a linear solve second =====\n\nStage 1 — genuine (M,n) states, directly, from an honest d=(λ1+1)(λ2+1)-dimensional diagonalization\nof the transfer matrix (no oversized Baxter-matrix proxy, hence no spurious extras possible):\n  • t2[λ1,λ2][1,1][u] = C0 + C1 u + C2 u^2 (coefficient matrices C0,C1,C2 pairwise commute).\n  • Diagonalize a GENERIC combination C0 + r C1 (Eigensystem) to get the common eigenvectors.\n  • For each eigenvector v, extract t0=(v.C0.v)/(v.v), t1=(v.C1.v)/(v.v) and verify the residuals\n    ||C0.v-t0 v||, ||C1.v-t1 v|| are ~0 — this residual check IS the new genuineness test (an\n    honest diagonalization can only fail this if there is a real construction bug, hence it is a\n    hard assertion, not a soft filter).\n  • Read off M ALGEBRAICALLY from t1 (τ0's u^1 coefficient is\n      -(θ1+θ2)(κ1+κ2) - h(κ1(λ1+λ2-M)+κ2 M),\n    and τ=τ0+J only shifts the u^0 term), so\n      M = [-(θ1+θ2)(κ1+κ2) - hκ1(λ1+λ2) - t1] / (h(κ2-κ1)),\n    asserted to land within 10^-10 of an integer — NOT inherited from a Baxter solve, NOT assigned\n    by continuity.\n  • Read off n within a fixed M-sector directly from J=t0 (τ0 has zero constant term), sorted\n    ascending by (Re[J],Im[J]) — same tie-break convention as the old approach — and assert the\n    resulting per-M count matches dPred(M) exactly (this is now a hard consistency check that MUST\n    pass by construction, not a post-hoc classification of genuine-vs-spurious).\n  This is built by TauEigensystem[λ1,λ2] (memoized per representation), with Psi[λ1,λ2][M,n] and\n  τ[λ1,λ2][M,n][u] as bounds-checked accessor wrappers. Psi::spurious is REPURPOSED from its old\n  meaning (\"Baxter root turned out fake\") to its new one: \"n is within the gross 0..M range but\n  exceeds the actual weight multiplicity dPred(M)-1\", which is the only failure mode left once the\n  diagonalization itself is exact.\n\nStage 2 — given the now-KNOWN genuine τ(u) (equivalently J_n) for a state (M,n), the Q-function is\nfound by a LINEAR NullSpace solve (not an eigenvalue problem, since τ is fixed): find the nullspace\nof BaxterMatrix[λ1,λ2,M] - J_n·Id (BaxterMatrix is the SAME (M+1)x(M+1) operator as before, just no\nlonger diagonalized — it is now evaluated at a single known J_n). This is QSolve[λ1,λ2][M,n], with\nQ1[λ1,λ2][M,n][u] = κ1^(u/h) q_n(u) the resulting wrapper. This NullSpace call uses an explicit\nChop (threshold 10^-12) of the matrix BEFORE calling NullSpace, together with an explicit\nTolerance->10^-10: at this ~28-digit working precision, a formally-zero matrix entry can still be\nrepresented as a precision-TRACKED zero (value 0 but finite Accuracy, e.g. printed as \"0``26\"),\nwhose Precision evaluates to ~0 and which NullSpace then treats as UNKNOWN rather than\nconfirmed-zero — silently returning an EMPTY nullspace for a matrix that is genuinely singular by\nconstruction. This bites the M=0 sector concretely (see the dedicated regression-guard cell) and,\nper the design brief, is exactly the same high-precision-NullSpace pitfall that historically bit\nthe (λ1,λ2,M,n)=(2,1,2,0) candidate in the superseded stacked-eigenvector construction; both the\nChop preprocessing and the explicit Tolerance are kept for robustness and that case is individually\nregression-tested below.\n\nBoth stages are validated end-to-end for λ1=λ2=1 (M=0,1,2) and the asymmetric λ1=2,λ2=1 (M=0..3,\nλ1+λ2=3) representations: stage 1 via a fresh (independent of C0/C1/C2) t2(u).Psi=τ(u)Psi check\nand a dPred-count match; stage 2 via the full original Baxter equation\na(u)Q(u+h)-τ(u)Q(u)+d(u)Q(u-h)=0 assembled entirely from the Q1/τ wrappers.\n\nConvention: q_n is stored as an ASCENDING coefficient list {c0,c1,...,cM} with cM=1, so that\nq_n(u) = {c0,...,cM} . {u^0,...,u^M} (helper qpoly).*)",
   "languageId": "markdown",
   "outputs": [],
   "metadata": {}
  },
  {
   "kind": 2,
   "value": "(*Numeric parameters (standalone solver — this file defines everything it needs).\n  Assigns global numeric values to θ1,θ2,h,κ1,κ2.*)\nθ1 = 1/3;\nθ2 = 1/7;\nh = 1;\nκ1 = N[Exp[I Zeta[3]], 30];\nκ2 = 1/κ1;\n{θ1, θ2, h, κ1, κ2}",
   "languageId": "wolfram",
   "outputs": [
    {
     "items": [
